                            Preamble

  The GNU Affero General Public License is a free, copyleft license
for software that adds certain benefits at distant locations.

  The benefits are:

  1. The license can be used for online services (software
  output delivered over a network) and encourages making the
  code freely available for use by users. This helps promote
  collaborative development of software that benefits all
  users.

  2. The license is a form of copyleft that requires distributed
  derivative works to carry forward the same freedoms that
  apply to the original software. It strengthens the principles
  of software freedom and encourages all users to cooperate
  in using, modifying, and distributing software that provides
  the ability to remotely run and interact with modified code
  ("debug mode").

  3. The license includes a protection for users working with
  modified versions of the software to ensure that they too
  have the freedom to study, modify, and distribute those
  modifications (including running the modified software
  remotely over a network). This protection is especially
  important for projects that provide essential services,
  because users can modify them to better meet their needs.

  4. Users who receive the software over a network can run and
  modify the software, and distribute copies of those
  modified versions to other users over the network, under
  the conditions of this license. This provides an additional
  benefit over previous versions of the license, which
  required the recipient of copies to print and ship them
  or manually download them.

  5. The license explicitly states that any modifications must
  be distributed under the same license, ensuring a strong
  form of software freedom and preventing attempts to
  incorporate the software into proprietary systems.

  This license was designed to work with the GNU General
  Public License (GPL), which provides the foundation for
  software freedom through its requirements of source code
  availability, modification permissions, and distribution
  obligations. The AGPL builds on these principles to address
  the specific challenges of network-distributed software.

                            License

  0. Definitions.

     "This License" refers to version 3 of the GNU Affero General
  Public License.

     "Copyright" also means copyright-like laws that apply to you
  (such as patent and trademark laws are excluded).  "Material"
  means any material for which the copyright status is not yet
  determined or is undetermined.

     "Modify" means to add to, delete from, or change the
  contents of this software or its portions, so that the
  software may function properly as a freeware, shareware, or
  public utility.

     "Propagate" means to cooperate in its full sense with
  the operation of the software in that it connects to other
  software in a distributed manner.  By modifying the
  software, you authorize it to be executed over a network
  by anyone who receives a copy of it, so that the software
  can be modified when it is used.

     To "convey" a work means any kind of propagation that
  enables other parties to make or receive copies.  Merely
  making a copy of the work does not affect the license
  except for conveying outside the bounds of the license.

     "You" (the licensee) means any individual or entity that
  uses the software or distributes it, except that you may be
  an individual or entity that first propagates or distributes
  code at the same time as the Original Author, and so you may
  not require you to consent to the license terms of subsequent
  distributors.  "Your" as a possessive means that something
  belongs to you; if you have received a copy of this software
  from the Original Author, you do not need to use the same
  license.

     "Source code" for a work means the preferred form of the
  work for making modifications, including the complete set
  of source files, configuration files needed to compile and
  install the work, and scripts used to control compilation
  and installation of the work.

     "You may treat" any covered work as freeware by adding
  both the required notice and using the GNU General Public
  License, GPL, and including the AGPLv3 terms for online
  software.

  1. Source Code Availability.

     a) You must make the source code of the covered work freely
  available for use by all users who access the software
  over a network, including anyone who receives a copy of
  the work via the network. This ensures that the software
  can be modified and studied by all users who interact with
  it remotely.

     b) The source code must be provided in the form of a
  machine-readable format that is commonly used for software
  interconnection. This typically means offering access to
  a version control system or a direct download of the source
  code files.

     c) You must prominently display the source code
  availability information on the software interface or in
  the documentation, making it clear how users can access
  the complete source code.

  2. Distribution and Modification.

     a) You may modify the software and distribute your
  modifications as long as you comply with the AGPLv3
  requirements, including making the source code available
  in the same manner as the original software.

     b) When you propagate a covered work, the recipient must
  be able to obtain the source code of that work, including
  any modifications you have made to it, in a form that
  allows them to modify and run it for their own purposes.

     c) You are required to retain all copyright notices, patent
  assignments, trademark notices, and disclaimers of
  warranty contained in the original software. If you omit
  any such notices, the work will be non-compliant with the
  license conditions.

  3. Network-Based Software Operation.

     a) If you provide the software over a network and
  users can receive copies of the software remotely,
  you must ensure that those users also have access to the
  source code, including any modifications you make.

     b) This requirement applies even if you provide
  additional software that enables users to modify the
  code remotely (debug mode). The purpose is to prevent
  users from being locked out of the software and its
  source code.

  4. Enforcement.

     a) You must conspicuously display the license terms
  and include the copyright notice in a manner that is
  clearly readable to users. This includes displaying the
  notice on the software interface or in the documentation.

     b) You may not impose any further restrictions on the
  exercise of the rights granted under this license. This
  includes prohibiting sublicense rights or imposing
  additional licensing requirements that would circumvent
  the license conditions.

  5. Exceptions.

     a) The license does not apply to independent, separate
  works that incorporate portions of this software but
  are not derivative works of it. In those cases, the
  license applies only to the contributed portions of the
  code.

     b) If you directly or indirectly prohibit users from
  complying with the license terms, your license
  modifications will be considered void under the
  provisions that prohibit user restrictions on the
  AGPLv3 license conditions.

